betterquesting:10.desc:8:
This pack has a very accelerated pregame, so we can jump into the fun as soon as possible.

To get you started on this journey, here are some §9Platinum Hammers§r, they mine in the 3x3 pattern, but you can can make them mine a single block by holding §cshift§r. Additionally, here is a §9prefab home§r and a §9§9satchel§r with §a§ra basic §aAE2§r network in it.

You may notice however, you lack a method to generate RF.
This first (pre)chapter lead you through the basics of premachine life, and some mods that you may find helpful.

This quest will be updated to refect custom oregen, if/when I do that. For now, the pack uses the default COFH world oregen, along with the addition of §ayung's better caves§r.

Take advantage of this by using the mineshaft that your prehab house generated, and mine near the bottom of the world.

Now that was fast, wasn't it?

The §9Steam Dynamo§r is your first power option, and is fairly simple, requiring water and a burnable item to generate RF. The easiest method to get water is with an §9Aqueous Accumulator§r. Note that §eRF can only be extracted through the coil§r (the red part) of the dynamo. Another quirk to note about thermal dynamos, is that they §ewill only push out power when they are generating power§r.

The Aqueous Accumulator§r will generate water based on how many §9water source blocks§r it is touching, with more source blocks will increase water generation. Use §9fluid ducts§r to pipe the water out, and into your dynamo.

Also, a bonus tip: wooden planks generate the same amount of RF as wood blocks.

The §9Morph-o-Tool §rcan mimic any number of wrenchs, hammers, or otherwise. To add a wrench-like item to it, §ccraft§r the §9§§Morph-o-Tool§r with the item.

You can change the wrench being displayed by §cscrolling while holding shift§r, in addition, when looking at block the wrench will mimic that givens mod's wrench. You can disable this by holding the wrench in the offhand.

§aPotion Fingers: Break The Barrier edition§r was a fork of the Potion Fingers mod created for another one of Pansmith's packs. The mod adds §9Rings§r§r that when equiped in an baubles, will grant the player with a buff that will last until the ring was removed §e(without potion swirls appearing)§r. Also, carrying two rings of the same type will cause the effect to be set to §6§estage two§r.

Let's make a trade.

§9Satchels§r, as you've likely noticed, can allow you to carry extra items, they can also be §cenchanted§r with holding to upgrade their capacity.

But in addition to that, there are also §9void satchels§r, which will automatically delete items that you set to be deleted.
The airhop enchantment gives the player extra jumps to use while in midair. The enchantment level refects how many midair jumps you have, and you §edo not use durability upon a midair jump§r.

You have no doubt used §adrawers§r before, but did you also know that you can upgrade them to increase their capacity, give off redstone signals, and more?

§cShift Right Click§r the drawer to open a GUI, where you can insert and remove upgrades. You can also §crightclick§r the drawer with the upgrade in your hand to insert it without needing the GUI.

This is a quick reference guide as to what the various colors and sizes mean in this questbook.

§7Text Colors
§9Blue§r = item 
§aGreen§r = mod 
§cRed§r = An action (such as rightclicking) 
§eYellow§r = Generally Important text 
§dPink§r = Important term

Terms will generally be highlighted only the first time they appear in a given quest.

§7Quest Sizes§r
Small = Normal Quest
Medium = Important concept, or a notible point in the chapter
Big = Start and end of the chapter.

The §9Drawer Controller§r allows you to easily insert/extract items into §9drawers§r. Any drawers that share a side with the drawer controller, or any drawers that share a side with the drawer controller (yes, this does repeat indefinitely, so you can make a big wall of drawers if you wanted to) can be have items be inserted into the controller, and it will get placed within the drawer, with the same being true for removing items.  Note that this means you can connect a drawer to a ME §9storage bus§r, and it §ewill automatically place items in those drawers§r, while still being visible to your network, saving space on your drives.

§9Drawer Slaves§r are basically extra insertion points into a drawer "network", and function the same as a drawer controller.

§9Trims§r are used to "extend" a drawer controllers reach, without having to worry about extra inventories.
No Description

The various §9keys§r added by §aStorage Drawers§r have a tool tip that explains what each key does. Note that with the §9drawer key§r§r, the drawer will be whitelisted to that item even when 0 copies are inside. 

Also, a §9key button§r is meant to be placed on a §9drawer controller§r, and will toggle that option on all drawers connected to said drawer controller.
The §9hang glider§r can be used to reach far away locations rather quickly!

AA comes with some §9placers§r and §9removers§r, these have the ability to place and mine up blocks and fluids, without requiring RF. While not needed for progression at this point in the pack §e(or ever, it depends on if in-world crafting is a topic that people request)§r, they still will come in handy if you decide to use Empowered Oil as your power source, which has been buffed in this pack.

Phantom Varitions of these two also exist, and function like a §9phantomface§r.

The §9machine frame§r is a microcrafting part that is in all of the §athermal expansion§r machine recipes.

§
The tabs on the side of a thermal machine are important, so lets talk about them quickly.

The topmost tab is the augmentation tab, this is where you can add and remove augments, once you have upgraded the machine to hardened.
You can also §crightclick§r the machine with augment to quick add it, as well.

The middle tab is the redstone control tab, it functions identically to the servo's redstone control.

The bottom tab is the configuration tab, this is where you can define the machine's §dIO§r (input/output). Note that §educts will only insert into a given machine's side if it is marked as input§r. Also, there are options are auto-input, and auto-output. These allow the machine to accept and export items to inventories, without the need for servos. This also applies to ducts. The rate that a given machine will auto-input and auto-output will increase when upgraded.

The first machine on your path to greatness, alloys metals together.

It can also be used to double your ores, at the cost of also requiring sand,

You may notice that there are extra options when configuring this machine's IO. These correlate to specfic slots, which are also highlighted when said option is selected.
Bronze is a alloy that will appear in various recipes in the earlygame, so keep some of this on hand.
The §9redstone furnace§r is pretty simple on it's own. It cooks items like a furnace, but uses RF instead of fuel.

The §9Energetic Infuser§r is used to recharge your items, as well as charge other materials, such as §9certus quartz§r.

Can be augmented to allow for wireless charging.

Makes plates, which are used in various recipes. 
Can also be augmented to create gears.

§9Tanks§r can be used to store fluids in large amounts. As the name implies, you can mine these tanks, and they will retain their fluids. §aThermal§r tanks also have the additional property of having IO on the bottom face,  (change with a wrench) so you could stack tanks on top of each other. This IO can be redstone controlled, this function can be enabled by §cshift rightclicking§r the tank.
The §9energy cell§r stores power, and like the tank, can be upgraded to hold more power. You can configure the cells IO, and how much rf is allowed to be imported and exported per tick.

§9Steel§r is an alloy that you will need a large amount of in the earlygame, so consider §dbulkcrafting§r it.

§dBulkcrafting§r is simply crafting a large amount of a given item at a time, this can apply to both manually crafting and using machines.

For example, place a chest and connect it to your induction smelter via IO, then place 128 §9coal§r and 32 §9iron§r inside of that chest. Over time, the smelter will process all of that into 32 steel, without you having to manually insert more items half way through.

This will be your main method of ore duplication for a while, with it being able to easily double your ores, without requiring §9sand§r. It can also crush ingots §rinto the dusts as well. It can also crush §9cobble§r into §9gravel§r, and gravel into sand.
No Description

§9Invar§r is a alloy that is rather useful in thermal, it allows you to craft §9hardened upgrade kits§r, and some augmentions. It this pack, it was also given some extra uses, such as being required in some machine recipes, and other alloys. However, invar is a bit finicky in this pack, and will only alloy if the §9nickel §ris a dust. Thankfully, the §9pulverizer§r you just crafted can do just that.

Tip: If you have a ore processing setup, use a §9filter§r to make sure that your nickel doesn't get smelted into ingots.

The §9Hardened Upgrade Kit§r is the first of four upgrade kits you can make. Along with making your machine faster and have a larger buffer,  these upgrades will allow you to install the previously afterforementioned augments into your machines and dynamos.
The regular method for creating §9fluix crystals§r has been disabled, so check JEI for the new methods. There are two of them, one of which becomes available once you obtain Fluix Steel.

§9Servos§r are used to extract items or fluids from inventories. By default, servos require redstone to work, and can be changed by §crightclicking§r them, and by changing it under the redstone control tab.

Servos can be filtered, to blacklist some items/fluids from being extracted. This function can be changed to be a whitelist function instead, by clicking on the warning sign in the servo's GUI. Items can be added to said list by clicking on a slot in the servo's GUI, while having the item selected, this will create a ghost item in that slot. For fluids, do the same, but with a bucket or tank containing the fluid that you want to add

As you make more advanced servos, they also gain more functions, alongside increased extraction rate: 

Basic:
§8§7§r§7NBT filtering (Fluid)§r - by default enabled, and will only extract fluids that share the exact nbt as the fluid in the filter.

Hardened:
§7Metadata filtering (Item)§r - Has the ability to extract only items that match the filter item's metadata, such as durablity or enchantments.

Reinforced:
§7NBT filtering (Item)§r - Will only extract items that share the exact nbt as the item in the filter.
§7Use Oredict (Item)§r - Will allow all items that share the same oredict as the filter item. This function is not relevent in this pack, as duplicate items have been removed. However, this function would be useful in a kitchensink pack.

Item destination options:
§7Nearest First§r - prioritises the destination it determines to have the closest path. Influnced by §9Vacuum and Dense Itemducts§7§r.
§7Furthest First§r - The inverse of the above.
§7Random§r - Chooses a random destination
§e§7Round Robin§r - §ewill cycle extracted stacks between all destination options, ignores Vacuum and Dense Itemducts. This is SUPER useful for automation!
§r 
{Embed}TypeLink;https://imgur.com/a/Uc0hKbP;90;20;Image Examples{Embed}

Signalium and Resonant Servos simply give an extra speed boost to items, along with having all the features of the Reinforced Servo.

A small crafting chain later, and you've got yourself some §9fluix ingots§r! These ingots will be used to get into making your own §aAE2§r stuff, as well as some other nice things.


It would be a good idea to craft some more of these while you are at it, as a easier method will present itself very soon.

Fun little tip for expert packs: if they gate §9flint and steel§r, you can simply cheese getting to the nether by using lava to set things on fire. Depending on the expert pack, this could be a large progression skip. 

Anyways, the nether is home to all the materials you know and love, as well as some §9nether ores§r. The nether will be an easier way to get §9emeralds§r in the earlygame, and you can find a §9diamond§r here and there as well.

Any ME Network requires power to run, simply place down your §9Energy Acceptor§r and connect it to a §9flux duct§r. (that has power, of course)




Note that most of the §aae2 §rrecipes in this pack diffculty will be unmodified, with some exceptions, such as the §9fluix crystal§r and §9circuits§r. (no more presses!)

Also, channels are disabled.

§9Cables§r are used to connect the various devices that make up your ME network together. Remeber, channels are disabled, so you do not have to worry about the amount of devices on your network. 

Also, remember that the §9chisel§9§r was given the ability to change the color of your cables, without needing dye!
The §9ME drive§r is what is used to store your items on your ME network, simply place it down and insert drives.

Let's be real, you already know what the §9chisel §rdoes. However, in this modpack, the chisel was given extra functionality. Along with being able to chisel blocks, it can change the states of some blocks. For example, it can §echange the color and coveredness§r of §9ME cables§r, the §etype§r of §9ME interface§r, and §echange the type§r of AA laser, without needing to use the §9atomic reconstructor§r.

Chiseled blocks can be automated with the autochisel. Place a §9chisel§r in the top middle slot, and place the block you want blocks to be chiseled in the bottom middle slot. You can use item pipes to automate inserting and extracting blocks (more info on how to do so is in the next chapter).
The§9 ender offset wand§r allows you to shift the texture of textures that connect with other blocks, which can be useful for looks in your base.
§9Invar§r opens up a decent number of power options, check them out!

A §9terminal§r is used to see the various items in your ME network. A §9crafting terminal§r functions just like a regular terminal, but with the added ability to let you craft while in the network. You can even use §aJEI§r's autofill function!

§9Hardened Fluiducts§r are just like the §9fluiducts§r you've been using, but can now transfer hot fluids!

Note that machines use fluids share the same IO behavior as those that don't, so refer to the machine frame recipe if you need a refresher.
The §9Magma Crucible§r allows you to be able to melt some items into fluids

The §9Fluid Transposer§r has three major uses: 

1. It can empty and fill containers, such as §9buckets§r and §9tanks§r. This can have some usage in automation.
2. It can extract fluids from some items
3. It can merge some fluids and items together.
These ingots are made by combining §9molten glowstone§r and §9invar§r together, and unlock some new options, such as §abonzi pots§r, and cheaper §9steel§r.

The §9Cell Workbench§r allows you to pertain what is on a given cell. This has two main uses: you can limit what is allowed to be stored on a specific cell. For example, you could have a cell that holds all of your cobbleworks related items on it. This becomes useful when you use the higher tiers of cells, and very useful if you are using §aExtracells§r cells. The other usage is like the above, but instead of using an actual cell, you would use a §9view cell§r. You then place the view cell in a §9terminal§r, and it §ewould black/white list those items appearing on that terminal§r.

betterquesting:10.name:8: An actual addition to your automation
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Crafted with §9Empowered Ingots§r, the §9Iron Casing§r is the starting point of §aActually Additions§r§r in this pack. Actually Additions brings a decent amount of features, some of which are amazing for automation. In this section, we will cover the most important parts of AA, and how to be best utilize them in automation.


§1For anyone playing, do you think that fluidcrafting and AA be split into their own chapters?
By crafting §9electrum§r, you gain access to §9reinforced upgrade kits§r, as well as some new options for power generation, so be sure to check that tab as well.

§9Retrievers§r are somewhat like a §9Servo§r and a §9Filter§r mixed into one, along with its own functions. A retriever will pull items or fluids towards themselves from other blocks connected to the duct network. Note that §iit will not pull from connections that have a servo attached to it§r. What makes these so powerful however, is the fact that §eyou can limit the amount of an item in the attached block§r (at higher tiers), and that these operate independently of each other, meaning they can be faster than servos on a large network.

Retrievers share the same exact upgrades as servos, so refer to that quest.

The §9ESD§r is a pretty neat device, it allows you to input and output from any side, and choose the exact range of slots it can pull from. The middle slot is meant for an §9item filter§r.  While it will be rather situational in this pack, it can come in handy in others.

§aThermal§r has a block with similar properties, called the §9Item Allocator§r.

The §9Atomic reconstructor§r allows you to transform ingots and gems into their §aAA§r counterparts, for use in crafting recipes, as well as various other recipes.

todo: add ae2 setup howto
One of the crafting components that makes up §aAA§r. The cost of these have been increased, so make sure you automated the §9atomic reconstructor§r.

§9Item Lasers§r are extermely helpful, and a big aid in your automation toolkit. A given Item Laser will read what ever block it is attached to and note the slots it has and what items are in them. These lasers can be connected made into a network by connecting said lasers with the §9laser wrench§r. 

The §9Item (Laser) Interface§r (refered to as the ILI from here on) is what is used to interact with an Item Laser network. The ILI can be used to insert and remove items from a given network. The way the Item Interface works is that it basically pretends to be a very large chest containing every slot of every container that is connected, but rather than storing the items within itself, any Items inserted and removed from the ILI will go to and be removed from the Item Laser Network. 

Also, you can set priority on a given item laser, to dictate where items will be pushed into first.

What makes this powerful is when you consider:
A. Priority
B. §aAE2§r §9Interface§r's blocking mode
C. A given machines behavor to only accept items it can process
D. Item Lasers near-infinite throughput


An example of how these lasers can greatly simplify setups can be found in the next quest.

Take 5 items, and combine them into one!

§HHave the §9empowerer§r in the middle, then have §9display stands§r 2 blocks out on each side of the empower, like this:

   D

D  E  D

   D

Refer to the ingame guide for picture examples, if needed.


When building your empowerment setup, rather than using §9item ducts§r and having to worry about filters and routing, simply place down five §9item lasers§r, one on each display stand, and one on the empowerer. Set the item laser on the empowerer to have a priority of one, and the rest to have a priority of zero, Then, place an §9ILI§r beside one of the lasers, then connect an §9Interface§r to that, §lwith blocking mode enabled§r.

What this does is that what item you have placed first in the processing pattern will always go the empowerer, with other four going to the display stands. Blocking mode will ensure that no extra groups of items will be inserted into the ILI while there are items still present in the item laser network. 

After that, have some method of exporting items from the empowerer, with it filtered to only extract the final product.

The §9Teleport Staff§r be used to teleport you to where you're looking. When you are looking at a block, it will teleport you there, however, when you aren't looking at a block, you can only be looking upwards up to 5 degrees, otherwise the teleport will fail.

This generator is rather simple: §9lava§r goes in, power comes out. §9Pyrothelium§r can be used for greater energy output. Note that while you lack a method to make lava that is rf positive right now, this method of generation is still very much viable early on, given the ease lava can be manually collected.
One of the two empowered crystals you will need, this one is pretty forward.

One of the two empowered materials needed for progression now, this one is pretty simple. Only thing to note is that this one needs §9bio-coal§o§r, which is made with the §9composter§r. Note that the composter will take up to 64 seeds at time, and will take a little while to craft, so automate it.

Congrats, you made it to the end of the pack!

For now, at the very least, this pack is in alpha after all.

Well, you more than likely got this pack from my discord, but if you got it from elsewhere, feel free to join. Any and all feedback, corrections, and suggestions are appreciated.

{Embed}TypeLink;https://discord.gg/N8b2JEfAqb;90;20;Discord{Embed}
Advanced Item lasers have the ablility to be filtered, in a way like the ESD.

Lasers have two modifications that can be applied to them:

Invisablity - Makes the green connection beam that shows that lasers are connected not render.
Range - Boosts laser max range from 15 blocks to 35 blocks.

§9Phantomfaces§r allow for remote interaction with inventories. §9Ducts§r, §9interfaces§r, and such will treat the phantomface as the inventory it is linked to, and will push/pull items into/out of the phantomface. These can allow you to massively compact your setups. To use them, rightclick the inventory you want to link with the §9phantom connector§r, then rightclick the phantomface you want to bind to it. Note that you can have multiple phantomfaces attached to a single inventory. 

They also come in variations that can place and break blocks at remote locations, as well as fluid and redstone varients as well.
Simply combine these with a block of your choice in a crafting table, and you will get 6 covers! These covers can be placed on §9ducts§r, much in the same way you would for §aae2 §9facades§r.
These tools use RF instead of durablity, and their mining radius can be changed as well. Upgrading will increase speed, rf storage, and the max radius that can be mined at once.

§9Worms§r can be gathered by tilling §9grass§r or §9dirt§r. When they are planted on Dirt or Grass, it will automatically till and hydrate the 3x3 area it is in. It will also cause the crops planted around it to grow slightly faster.
Does exactly what the tooltip says - blocks natural mob spawning in a large radius, so spawners will still work.
An alterative to the §9Mega Torch§r, it does what the tooltip says.
Same deal as the §9reactant dynamo§r, while the dynamo itself doesn't need §9invar§r, the machines required to give it use do.
Using §9boiler§r and §9turbine augments§r will allow you to double your power output vs just not using any augment in a §9steam dyanmo§r. The ideal ratio of boilers to turbines should be 2:1.

This one is a bit more set up intensive, but the power output can be worth it, especially with it's augment.

While the machine itself doesn't require §9invar§r, the §9magma crucible§r does.
§9Electrium§r grants you access to some more funky ways to generate power, such as with§9 diamonds§r.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Putting the Redstone back into Redstone Flux
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Redstone goes in, Redstone Flux comes out. 

What's not to love?
Paying for power, quite literally.
The §9Fractioning Still§r allows you to refine some fluids into others, and can even be used to make potions stronger.

A small crafting chain later, and you've got yourself some §9fluix ingots§r! These ingots will be used to get into making your own §aAE2§r stuff, as well as some other nice things.


It would be a good idea to craft some more of these while you are at it, as a easier method will present itself very soon.

The §9ME storage cells§r are what actually store your items on the ME network. A given storage cell has two limits, the §t§dtype§r limit, and a §b§dbyte§r limit. 

The §dtype§r limit dicates that only§l 63§r unique item §dtypes§o§r (not stacks) may be stored in a given cell. Note that items with specific NBT data (such as a damaged tool) can not stack with other items that do not share that exact same NBT data, even if they are of the same §etype§r. 

The §dbyte§r limit dicates how many items (not types) can be stored in a given cell. This can be upgraded to allow more items to be stored in a single cell. For items that you will have a massive amount of, it is a good practice to use a §9Storage bus§r to store them off your network (but still seen by your network) in a §9drawer (controller)§r or similar.

Notice what when attempting to craft something, you will see that it will require bytes in order to craft. These bytes are supplied by Crafting CPUs. Crafting CPUs are made by placing 1 or more §9crafting storage units§r in a cube or rectangle shape, then connecting it to your ME system via a cable. You can use "empty" crafting unit to fill out a crafting CPU multiblock, if needed.

Does exactly what the title does - makes the §9Fluix§r and §9Fluix Steel §rrecipes cheaper and easier to make.

Something to note about this machine (and all §aLazyAE2§a§r machines), it accepts both RF and AE, so you can connect it to either a §9ME cable§r or a §9flux duct§r. (or an equivent) Also, you can configure it's IO in the top right of it's GUI.

As previously mentioned, presses do not exist in this pack, rather, §9circuits§r are handled through the §alazyae2§r §9inscriber§r. These will what will enable to start crafting your own AE2 devices.

I would recommend going and crafting the §9fluix aggreator§r, if you haven't already. It will simplify the §9fluix§r recipe by a large margain.
Allows you to make pure crystals at a rate faster than vanilla AE2's §l8 hour§r growth time.

§9Formation and Destruction Planes§r are used to place, drop, and break items and fluids in the world. Within the blocks GUI, You can set what objects are allowed, and you can toggle between placing, and dropping an item into the world (if it is a formation plane).

betterquesting:10.name:8: The only IO you will need.
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
§9Interfaces§r are extremely useful, if not outright the best tool in your §aae2§r arsenal.

Alongside allowing the player to autocraft (more on that in the next quest), they also §ecan IO from your network at extreme speeds, while being much less laggy then import/export busses, on top on not requring any upgrades to work at optimal speeds.§r

To have items be exported, place the item in one of the slots with the downwards arrow on it. The amount of items set will dicate how many items held in that interface. §eFor example, placing 4 dirt blocks will ensure that the interface will always try to have 4 dirt blocks inside of it§r. If you don't care about that function, just place a stack in there for max throughput. You can then export the items from the interface. Importing items back into the network is just a matter of piping items into the interface, like how you would a chest. §cRightclicking§r the interface with a wrench will set it to only export items from the side indicated via the arrows, this comes more into play when you start autocrafting. 

§9Fluid interfaces§r work in a similar way, define what fluids you want to be exported via the top row. 

§eRemember that in this pack, you can switch the various interface types with a chisel§r.
No Description

§9Patterns§r are used to encode crafting table and processing recipes, to be used in autocrafting.

Crafting table recipes are used in the §9molecular assembler§r, while processing recipes are used in everything else.


Note that when using §9interfaces§r, §eyou can have a given machine both input and output from a single side§r. This is useful for single step operations, such as making plates

Todo: explain pattern mechanics

Get into the habit of naming your §9interfaces§r, as this block will making inserting and removing patterns nicer. This terminal will be able to see all the interfaces on your network, and will allow you to remotely insert and remove patterns from them. You can search by both the name of the interface, and the interface's output. §eIf you do not want an interface to appear here, simply click on the interface terminal button in the top left of the interface's GUI§r.

If you didn't already know, you can name interfaces in an anvil, no inscriber needed.
Seriously, don't.
§9Facades§r can be used to hide your cables, simply place one on a device or a wire.
Basically storage cells, but for fluids.
Adding §9Crafting Coprocessing Units§r to your Crafting CPU multiblock will allow it to complete multiaple tasks at once, with each coprocessing unit added allowing it to complete another task.
Adding this to your Crafting CPU multiblock will have it display whatever that CPU is currently crafting, simple as that.

§9Crafting Cards§r can be used to automate autocrafting items in your network.

However, you should generally just passive rather than using crafting cards, as constantly attempting large orders will cause your network to lag.

As mentioned before, these are used to craft crafting table recipes. Simply place the §9assembler§r beside the §9interface §rwith said patterns in it, and it will craft the items, handing all of the IO itself. Note that interfaces and assemblers will transfer ME power, so you could surround a interface with assemblers to allow it to craft 6 things at once, or even build a lattice of interfaces and assemblers (This is when the §9§9pattern terminal§r really comes in handy, as you can remotely insert and remove patterns).

Yes, this quest's requirements are gimped intentionally. This stuff will come in a later update. Good on you for checking with §7bq_admin edit§r, though.

Well, while you are here, check this out:

Did you know that the predicted time for beating §aSuper Mario 64 DS§r without the jump button is §eover 20,000 years§r? This is due to the §dremote interaction glitch§r. While this glitch allows the player to obtain stars and coins that are out of reach, it has the slight downside of taking some time to set up, ranging anywhere from 100 to 1000+ years, depending on how fast you can spawn entities.

Acts as a storage bus, but allows you to define what is allowed to be used on it via oredict. The GUI goes into to detail on how to use the filter.

The §9Canola Press§r does exactly what you think it does - turn §9canola seeds§r into oil.

Note that all §aAA§r machines have a tab in §aJEI§r that will give more information about that machine.

A early method to automatically gather ores, how nice is that? 

The §9Vertical Digger§r does exactly what the name implies, it will mine blocks under it, with a radius of 5x5, centered on the digger. It has two modes: "Mining Everything" and "Only Mining Ores", which does what it describes. It's radius is doubled when a §9Phantom Booster§r is placecd on top of it, and this can be stacked up to three times, leading to a radius of 33x33.
Make sure you have §9empowered§r and §9infused ingots§r automated.

The first step into §aAA§r, §9empowered ingots§r are used to craft AA's §9machine hulls§r. 

Note how the ingot's recipe has a bucket in it. This may lead you to think that you may need some complicated setup to keep filled buckets passived, but there is a much easier way. The §9Sequential Fabricator§r, when given a §9Fluidic Fabrication§r augment, §ecan handle fluidcrafting§r. Simply set up the recipe as you would in a crafting table (or use §aJEI§r's autofill function), then insert the fluid into the machine. The recipe itself will not require buckets once you do that, so make sure you remove it from your autocrafting pattern.

§9Coke§r has a couple of uses, but it's main one is having a much better ratio compared to §9coal§r when making §9steel§r. 

Also, §9creosote§r will have some uses in the future, so feel free to hold onto it.

§9Bonzi Pots§r are pretty neat. They allow you to easily grow trees without having to worry about chopping and replanting, and all of that. All you need to do is §crightclick§r the pot with §9dirt§r, followed by the§9 sapling§r of your choice. In this pack, they have been buffed a bit as well, to aid in making earlygame power production (and coke production) easier.

Tip: §9Wood§r and §9wooden planks§r will burn into the same amount of steam. The §9carpenter§r may be of use here.
The §9farmer§r will farm in an 9x9 area in front of it, and will auto-till §9grass§r as needed.

§9Elevators§r are pretty simple, place one somewhere above or below another elevator, and you can warp between the two. §cJump§r to go up, §cCrouch§r to go down. You can also have more than 2 elevators, and they will still work as you would expect.

§9Filters§r will filter what is allowed to enter the destination it is attached to.

Basic:
§8§7§r§7NBT filtering (Fluid)§r - by default enabled, and will only extract fluids that share the exact nbt as the fluid in the filter.

Hardened:
§7Metadata filtering (Item)§r - Has the ability to extract only items that match the filter item's metadata, such as durablity or enchantments.

Reinforced:
§7NBT filtering (Item)§r - Will only extract items that share the exact nbt as the item in the filter.
§7Use Oredict (Item)§r - Will allow all items that share the same oredict as the filter item. This function is not relevent in this pack, as duplicate items have been removed. However, this function would be useful in a kitchensink pack.

§9Ducts§r are your main method of moving items and fluids for a decent part of this pack. Items are extracted from inventories (machines output slots, chests, etc) with §9servos§r (more info can be found in it's own quest), and are inserted into applicable destinations.

Note that item movement is not instant with ducts, and this can be easily illustrated with clear ducts. The travel speed of items can be influenced via §9
impulse itemducts§r.

§9Dense and vacuum itemducts§r§r are used to influenced pathing logic - more info on that can be found in the servo quest.

A very accelerated start, but a start nevertheless.

This chapter covers the basics of this pack, and what you should expect, as well as some other items and mods that would be useful in the earlygame.
